# UI minimal copy — agent reference

**Default:** do not add UI text. Extra labels, subtitles, helper paragraphs, card descriptions, and explanatory banners make the app noisy and harder to maintain.

Unless the user asks for copy or it is **really needed**, add **no** new text.

## Really needed (allowed)

- **Form field labels** — short; required for usability and WCAG (`accessibility` skill).
- **Primary actions** — short button text (`Save`, `Send`, `Cancel`).
- **Errors / validation** — only when something failed or input is invalid.
- **Destructive confirms** — one short line stating what will happen.
- **Legal / compliance** — only when product requires it.
- **Icon-only controls** — `aria-label` / `title` (short, not a paragraph).

## Do not add unless asked

- Page or section subtitles under an already-clear title
- `CardDescription`, helper text under fields, "tip" callouts
- Empty-state essays — prefer icon + one short line, or nothing
- Inline "this lets you…" / "use this to…" explanations
- Duplicating data already visible (dates, names, status badges)
- Marketing-style microcopy on admin or operational screens

## When building or editing UI

1. Ship layout, hierarchy, icons, and data first.
2. Add text only where the screen would be unusable without it.
3. If unsure, **omit** — the user will ask for copy when they want it.
4. Read the `minimal-ui-copy` skill for patterns and examples.

## Conflicts

- `accessibility` still requires labels for inputs and icon buttons — keep those **short**.
- `frontend-design` density guidance stands; this rule wins on **verbosity**, not structure.
